<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A=20
id=3Dintro></A>Introduction</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>In the world of <A class=3Dulink=20
href=3D"http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/hacker-howto.html" =
target=3D_top>hackers</A>,=20
the kind of answers you get to your technical questions depends as much =
on the=20
way you ask the questions as on the difficulty of developing the answer. =
This=20
guide will teach you how to ask questions in a way more likely to get =
you a=20
satisfactory answer.</P>
<P>Now that use of open source has become widespread, you can often get =
as good=20
answers from other, more experienced users as from hackers. This is a =
Good=20
Thing; users tend to be just a little bit more tolerant of the kind of =
failures=20
newbies often have. Still, treating experienced users like hackers in =
the ways=20
we recommend here will generally be the most effective way to get useful =
answers=20
out of them, too.</P>
<P>The first thing to understand is that hackers actually like hard =
problems and=20
good, thought-provoking questions about them. If we didn't, we wouldn't =
be here.=20
If you give us an interesting question to chew on we'll be grateful to =
you; good=20
questions are a stimulus and a gift. Good questions help us develop our=20
understanding, and often reveal problems we might not have noticed or =
thought=20
about otherwise. Among hackers, =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Good =
question!</SPAN>=E2=80=9D is a=20
strong and sincere compliment.</P>
<P>Despite this, hackers have a reputation for meeting simple questions =
with=20
what looks like hostility or arrogance. It sometimes looks like we're=20
reflexively rude to newbies and the ignorant. But this isn't really =
true.</P>
<P>What we are, unapologetically, is hostile to people who seem to be =
unwilling=20
to think or to do their own homework before asking questions. People =
like that=20
are time sinks =E2=80=94 they take without giving back, and they waste =
time we could=20
have spent on another question more interesting and another person more =
worthy=20
of an answer. We call people like this =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>losers</SPAN>=E2=80=9D (and=20
for historical reasons we sometimes spell it =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>lusers</SPAN>=E2=80=9D).</P>
<P>We realize that there are many people who just want to use the =
software we=20
write, and who have no interest in learning technical details. For most =
people,=20
a computer is merely a tool, a means to an end; they have more important =
things=20
to do and lives to live. We acknowledge that, and don't expect everyone =
to take=20
an interest in the technical matters that fascinate us. Nevertheless, =
our style=20
of answering questions is tuned for people who <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>do</EM></SPAN> take such an interest and are =
willing to be=20
active participants in problem-solving. That's not going to change. Nor =
should=20
it; if it did, we would become less effective at the things we do =
best.</P>
<P>We're (largely) volunteers. We take time out of busy lives to answer=20
questions, and at times we're overwhelmed with them. So we filter =
ruthlessly. In=20
particular, we throw away questions from people who appear to be losers =
in order=20
to spend our question-answering time more efficiently, on winners.</P>
<P>If you find this attitude obnoxious, condescending, or arrogant, =
check your=20
assumptions. We're not asking you to genuflect to us =E2=80=94 in fact, =
most of us would=20
love nothing more than to deal with you as an equal and welcome you into =
our=20
culture, if you put in the effort required to make that possible. But =
it's=20
simply not efficient for us to try to help people who are not willing to =
help=20
themselves. It's OK to be ignorant; it's not OK to play stupid.</P>
<P>So, while it isn't necessary to already be technically competent to =
get=20
attention from us, it <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>is</EM></SPAN> =
necessary to=20
demonstrate the kind of attitude that leads to competence =E2=80=94 =
alert, thoughtful,=20
observant, willing to be an active partner in developing a solution. If =
you=20
can't live with this sort of discrimination, we suggest you pay somebody =
for a=20
commercial support contract instead of asking hackers to personally =
donate help=20
to you.</P>
<P>If you decide to come to us for help, you don't want to be one of the =
losers.=20
You don't want to seem like one, either. The best way to get a rapid and =

responsive answer is to ask it like a person with smarts, confidence, =
and clues=20
who just happens to need help on one particular problem.</P>
<P>(Improvements to this guide are welcome. You can mail suggestions to =
<A=20
class=3Dulink href=3D"mailto:esr@thyrsus.com" =
target=3D_top>esr@thyrsus.com</A> or <A=20
class=3Dulink =
href=3D"http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/respond-auto@linuxmafia.com"=20
target=3D_top>http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/respond-auto@linuxmafia.com</=
A>. Note=20
however that this document is not intended to be a general guide to <A=20
class=3Dulink href=3D"http://www.dtcc.edu/cs/rfc1855.html"=20
target=3D_top>netiquette</A>, and we will generally reject suggestions =
that are=20
not specifically related to eliciting useful answers in a technical=20
forum.)</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dbefore></A>Before You=20
Ask</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Before asking a technical question by e-mail, or in a newsgroup, or =
on a=20
website chat board, do the following:</P>
<DIV class=3Dprocedure>
<OL type=3D1>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by searching the archives of the forum you =
plan to=20
  post to.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by searching the Web.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by reading the manual.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by reading a FAQ.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by inspection or experimentation.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Try to find an answer by asking a skilled friend.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>If you're a programmer, try to find an answer by reading the source =

  code.</P></LI></OL></DIV>
<P>When you ask your question, display the fact that you have done these =
things=20
first; this will help establish that you're not being a lazy sponge and =
wasting=20
people's time. Better yet, display what you have <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>learned</EM></SPAN> from doing these things. We =
like=20
answering questions for people who have demonstrated they can learn from =
the=20
answers.</P>
<P>Use tactics like doing a Google search on the text of whatever error =
message=20
you get (searching <A class=3Dulink href=3D"http://groups.google.com/"=20
target=3D_top>Google groups</A> as well as Web pages). This might well =
take you=20
straight to fix documentation or a mailing list thread answering your =
question.=20
Even if it doesn't, saying =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>I googled on the =
following phrase=20
but didn't get anything that looked promising</SPAN>=E2=80=9D is a good =
thing to do in=20
e-mail or news postings requesting help, if only because it records what =

searches won't help. It will also help to direct other people with =
similar=20
problems to your thread by linking the search terms to what will =
hopefully be=20
your problem and resolution thread.</P>
<P>Take your time. Do not expect to be able to solve a complicated =
problem with=20
a few seconds of Googling. Read and understand the FAQs, sit back, relax =
and=20
give the problem some thought before approaching experts. Trust us, they =
will be=20
able to tell from your questions how much reading and thinking you did, =
and will=20
be more willing to help if you come prepared. Don't instantly fire your =
whole=20
arsenal of questions just because your first search turned up no answers =
(or too=20
many).</P>
<P>Prepare your question. Think it through. Hasty-sounding questions get =
hasty=20
answers, or none at all. The more you do to demonstrate that having put =
thought=20
and effort into solving your problem before seeking help, the more =
likely you=20
are to actually get help.</P>
<P>Beware of asking the wrong question. If you ask one that is based on =
faulty=20
assumptions, J. Random Hacker is quite likely to reply with a uselessly =
literal=20
answer while thinking =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Stupid =
question...</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, and hoping=20
the experience of getting what you asked for rather than what you needed =
will=20
teach you a lesson.</P>
<P>Never assume you are <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>entitled</EM></SPAN> =
to an=20
answer. You are not; you aren't, after all, paying for the service. You =
will=20
earn an answer, if you earn it, by asking a substantial, interesting, =
and=20
thought-provoking question =E2=80=94 one that implicitly contributes to =
the experience=20
of the community rather than merely passively demanding knowledge from=20
others.</P>
<P>On the other hand, making it clear that you are able and willing to =
help in=20
the process of developing the solution is a very good start. =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Would someone provide a pointer?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>What is=20
my example missing?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, and =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>What site should I have=20
checked?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D are more likely to get answered than =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Please=20
post the exact procedure I should use.</SPAN>=E2=80=9D because you're =
making it clear=20
that you're truly willing to complete the process if someone can just =
point you=20
in the right direction.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dasking></A>When You=20
Ask</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dforum></A>Choose your forum=20
carefully</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Be sensitive in choosing where you ask your question. You are likely =
to be=20
ignored, or written off as a loser, if you:</P>
<DIV class=3Ditemizedlist>
<UL type=3Ddisc>
  <LI>
  <P>post your question to a forum where it's off topic</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>post a very elementary question to a forum where advanced technical =

  questions are expected, or vice-versa</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>cross-post to too many different newsgroups</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>post a personal e-mail to somebody who is neither an acquaintance =
of yours=20
  nor personally responsible for solving your =
problem</P></LI></UL></DIV>
<P>Hackers blow off questions that are inappropriately targeted in order =
to try=20
to protect their communications channels from being drowned in =
irrelevance. You=20
don't want this to happen to you.</P>
<P>The first step, therefore, is to find the right forum. Again, Google =
and=20
other Web-searching methods are your friend. Use them to find the =
project=20
webpage most closely associated with the hardware or software giving you =

difficulties. Usually it will have links to a FAQ (Frequently Asked =
Questions)=20
list, and to project mailing lists and their archives. These mailing =
lists are=20
the final places to go for help, if your own efforts (including <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>reading</EM></SPAN> those FAQs you found) do not =
find you a=20
solution. The project page may also describe a bug-reporting procedure, =
or have=20
a link to one; if so, follow it.</P>
<P>Shooting off an e-mail to a person or forum which you are not =
familiar with=20
is risky at best. For example, do not assume that the author of an =
informative=20
webpage wants to be your free consultant. Do not make optimistic guesses =
about=20
whether your question will be welcome =E2=80=94 if you're unsure, send =
it elsewhere, or=20
refrain from sending it at all.</P>
<P>When selecting a Web forum, newsgroup or mailing list, don't trust =
the name=20
by itself too far; look for a FAQ or charter to verify your question is=20
on-topic. Read some of the back traffic before posting so you'll get a =
feel for=20
how things are done there. In fact, it's a very good idea to do a =
keyword search=20
for words relating to your problem on the newsgroup or mailing list =
archives=20
before you post. It may find you an answer, and if not it will help you=20
formulate a better question.</P>
<P>Don't shotgun-blast all the available help channels at once, that's =
like=20
yelling and irritates people. Step through them softly.</P>
<P>Know what your topic is! One of the classic mistakes is asking =
questions=20
about the Unix or Windows programming interface in a forum devoted to a =
language=20
or library or tool portable across both. If you don't understand why =
this is a=20
blunder, you'd be best off not asking any questions at all until you get =
it.</P>
<P>In general, questions to a well-selected public forum are more likely =
to get=20
useful answers than equivalent questions to a private one. There are =
multiple=20
reasons for this. One is simply the size of the pool of potential =
respondents.=20
Another is the size of the audience; hackers would rather answer =
questions that=20
educate many people than questions serving only a few.</P>
<P>Understandably, skilled hackers and authors of popular software are =
already=20
receiving more than their fair share of mis-targeted messages. By adding =
to the=20
flood, you could in extreme cases even be the straw that breaks the =
camel's back=20
=E2=80=94 quite a few times, contributors to popular projects have =
withdrawn their=20
support because collateral damage in the form of useless e-mail traffic =
to their=20
personal accounts became unbearable.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dusefora></A>Web and IRC forums directed =
towards newbies=20
often give the quickest response</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Your local user group, or your Linux distribution, may advertise a =
Web forum=20
or IRC channel where newbies can get help. (In non-English-speaking =
countries=20
newbie forums are still more likely to be mailing lists.) These are good =
first=20
places to ask, especially if you think you may have tripped over a =
relatively=20
simple or common problem. An advertised IRC channel is an open =
invitation to ask=20
questions there and often get answers in real time.</P>
<P>In fact, if you got the program that is giving you problems from a =
Linux=20
distribution (as is common today), it may be better to ask in the =
distro's=20
forum/list before trying the program's project forum/list. The project's =
hackers=20
may just say, =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>use <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>our</EM></SPAN>=20
build</SPAN>=E2=80=9D.</P>
<P>Before posting to any Web forum, check if it has a Search feature. If =
it=20
does, try a couple of keyword searches for something like your problem; =
it just=20
might help. If you did a general Web search before (as you should have), =
search=20
the forum anyway; your Web-wide search engine might not have all of this =
forum=20
indexed recently.</P>
<P>There is an increasing tendency for projects to do user support over =
a Web=20
forum or IRC channel, with e-mail reserved more for development traffic. =
So look=20
for those channels first when seeking project-specific help.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Duselists></A>As a second step, use project =
mailing=20
lists</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>When a project has a development mailing list, write to the mailing =
list, not=20
to individual developers, even if you believe you know who can best =
answer your=20
question. Check the documentation of the project and its homepage for =
the=20
address of a project mailing list, and use it. There are several good =
reasons=20
for this policy:</P>
<DIV class=3Ditemizedlist>
<UL type=3Ddisc>
  <LI>
  <P>Any question good enough to be asked of one developer will also be =
of value=20
  to the whole group. Contrariwise, if you suspect your question is too =
dumb for=20
  a mailing list, it's not an excuse to harass individual =
developers.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Asking questions on the list distributes load among developers. The =

  individual developer (especially if he's the project leader) may be =
too busy=20
  to answer your questions.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Most mailing lists are archived and the archives are indexed by =
search=20
  engines. If you ask your question on-list and it is answered, a future =
querent=20
  could find your question and the answer on the Web instead of asking =
it=20
  again.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>If certain questions are seen to be asked often, developers can use =
that=20
  information to improve the documentation or the software itself to be =
less=20
  confusing. But if those questions are asked in private, nobody has the =

  complete picture of what questions are asked most =
often.</P></LI></UL></DIV>
<P>If a project has both a =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>user</SPAN>=E2=80=9D and a =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>developer</SPAN>=E2=80=9D (or =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>hacker</SPAN>=E2=80=9D) mailing=20
list or Web forum, and you are not hacking on the code, ask in the =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>user</SPAN>=E2=80=9D list/forum. Do not assume that you =
will be welcome on=20
the developer list, where they're likely to experience your question as =
noise=20
disrupting their developer traffic.</P>
<P>However, if you are <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>sure</EM></SPAN> your =
question=20
is non-trivial, and you get no answer in the =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>user</SPAN>=E2=80=9D=20
list/forum for several days, try the =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>developer</SPAN>=E2=80=9D one.=20
You would be well advised to lurk there for a few days before posting to =
learn=20
the local folkways (actually this is good advice on any private or =
semi-private=20
list).</P>
<P>If you cannot find a project's mailing list address, but only see the =
address=20
of the maintainer of the project, go ahead and write to the maintainer. =
But even=20
in that case, don't assume that the mailing list doesn't exist. Mention =
in your=20
e-mail that you tried and could not find the appropriate mailing list. =
Also=20
mention that you don't object to having your message forwarded to other =
people.=20
(Many people believe that private e-mail should remain private, even if =
there is=20
nothing secret in it. By allowing your message to be forwarded you give =
your=20
correspondent a choice about how to handle your e-mail.)</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dbespecific></A>Use meaningful, specific =
subject=20
headers</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>On mailing lists, newsgroups or Web forums, the subject header is =
your golden=20
opportunity to attract qualified experts' attention in around 50 =
characters or=20
fewer. Don't waste it on babble like =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Please =
help me</SPAN>=E2=80=9D=20
(let alone =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>PLEASE HELP =
ME!!!!</SPAN>=E2=80=9D; messages with subjects=20
like that get discarded by reflex). Don't try to impress us with the =
depth of=20
your anguish; use the space for a super-concise problem description =
instead.</P>
<P>One good convention for subject headers, used by many tech support=20
organizations, is =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>object - =
deviation</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. The =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>object</SPAN>=E2=80=9D part specifies what thing or group =
of things is=20
having a problem, and the =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>deviation</SPAN>=E2=80=9D part describes=20
the deviation from expected behavior.</P>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN>=20
  </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>HELP! Video doesn't work properly on my laptop!</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN=20
  class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN></SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>X.org 6.8.1 misshapen mouse cursor, Fooware MV1005 vid. =
chipset</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN=20
  class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smarter:</STRONG></SPAN></SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>X.org 6.8.1 mouse cursor on Fooware MV1005 vid. chipset - is=20
  misshapen</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<P>The process of writing an =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>object-deviation</SPAN>=E2=80=9D=20
description will help you organize your thinking about the problem in =
more=20
detail. What is affected? Just the mouse cursor or other graphics too? =
Is this=20
specific to the X.org version of X? To version 6.8.1? Is this specific =
to=20
Fooware video chipsets? To model MV1005? A hacker who sees the result =
can=20
immediately understand what it is that you are having a problem with =
<SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>and</EM></SPAN> the problem you are having, at a =
glance.</P>
<P>More generally, imagine looking at the index of an archive of =
questions, with=20
just the subject lines showing. Make your subject line reflect your =
question=20
well enough that the next guy searching the archive with a question =
similar to=20
yours will be able to follow the thread to an answer rather than posting =
the=20
question again.</P>
<P>If you ask a question in a reply, be sure to change the subject line =
to=20
indicate that you're asking a question. A Subject line that looks like =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Re: test</SPAN>=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>Re: new bug</SPAN>=E2=80=9D is less=20
likely to attract useful amounts of attention. Also, pare quotation of =
previous=20
messages to the minimum consistent with cluing in new readers.</P>
<P>Do not simply hit reply to a list message in order to start an =
entirely new=20
thread. This will limit your audience. Some mail readers, like mutt, =
allow the=20
user to sort by thread and then hide messages in a thread by folding the =
thread.=20
Folks who do that will never see your message.</P>
<P>Changing the subject is not sufficient. Mutt, and probably other mail =

readers, looks at other information in the e-mail's headers to assign it =
to a=20
thread, not the subject line. Instead start an entirely new e-mail.</P>
<P>On Web forums the rules of good practice are slightly different, =
because=20
messages are usually much more tightly bound to specific discussion =
threads and=20
often invisible outside those threads. Changing the subject when asking =
a=20
question in reply is not essential. Not all forums even allow separate =
subject=20
lines on replies, and nearly nobody reads them when they do. However, =
asking a=20
question in a reply is a dubious practice in itself, because it will =
only be=20
seen by those who are watching this thread. So, unless you are sure you =
<SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>want</EM></SPAN> to ask only the people currently =
active in=20
the thread, start a new one.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Deasyreply></A>Make it easy to =
reply</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Finishing your query with =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Please send =
your reply to...=20
</SPAN>=E2=80=9D makes it quite unlikely you will get an answer. If you =
can't be=20
bothered to take even the few seconds required to set up a correct =
Reply-To=20
header in your mail agent, we can't be bothered to take even a few =
seconds to=20
think about your problem. If your mail program doesn't permit this, <A=20
class=3Dulink href=3D"http://linuxmafia.com/faq/Mail/muas.html" =
target=3D_top>get a=20
better mail program</A>. If your operating system doesn't support any =
e-mail=20
programs that permit this, get a better operating system.</P>
<P>In Web forums, asking for a reply by e-mail is outright rude, unless =
you=20
believe the information may be sensitive (and somebody will, for some =
unknown=20
reason, let you but not the whole forum know it). If you want an e-mail =
copy=20
when somebody replies in the thread, request that the Web forum send it; =
this=20
feature is supported almost everywhere under options like =E2=80=9C<SPAN =

class=3Dquote>watch this thread</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>send e-mail on=20
answers</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, etc.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dwritewell></A>Write in clear, grammatical,=20
correctly-spelled language</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>We've found by experience that people who are careless and sloppy =
writers are=20
usually also careless and sloppy at thinking and coding (often enough to =
bet on,=20
anyway). Answering questions for careless and sloppy thinkers is not =
rewarding;=20
we'd rather spend our time elsewhere.</P>
<P>So expressing your question clearly and well is important. If you =
can't be=20
bothered to do that, we can't be bothered to pay attention. Spend the =
extra=20
effort to polish your language. It doesn't have to be stiff or formal =
=E2=80=94 in fact,=20
hacker culture values informal, slangy and humorous language used with=20
precision. But it has to <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>be</EM></SPAN> =
precise; there=20
has to be some indication that you're thinking and paying attention.</P>
<P>Spell, punctuate, and capitalize correctly. Don't confuse =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>its</SPAN>=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>it's</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>loose</SPAN>=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>lose</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, or =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>discrete</SPAN>=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>discreet</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. Don't=20
TYPE IN ALL CAPS; this is read as shouting and considered rude. =
(All-smalls is=20
only slightly less annoying, as it's difficult to read. Alan Cox can get =
away=20
with it, but you can't.)</P>
<P>More generally, if you write like a semi-literate boob you will very =
likely=20
be ignored. So don't use instant-messaging shortcuts. Spelling "you" as =
"u"=20
makes you look like a semi-literate boob to save two entire keystrokes. =
Worse:=20
writing like a l33t script kiddie hax0r is the absolute kiss of death =
and=20
guarantees you will receive nothing but stony silence (or, at best, a =
heaping=20
helping of scorn and sarcasm) in return.</P>
<P>If you are asking questions in a forum that does not use your native=20
language, you will get a limited amount of slack for spelling and =
grammar errors=20
=E2=80=94 but no extra slack at all for laziness (and yes, we can =
usually spot that=20
difference). Also, unless you know what your respondent's languages are, =
write=20
in English. Busy hackers tend to simply flush questions in languages =
they don't=20
understand, and English is the working language of the Internet. By =
writing in=20
English you minimize your chances that your question will be discarded=20
unread.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dformats></A>Send questions in accessible, =
standard=20
formats</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>If you make your question artificially hard to read, it is more =
likely to be=20
passed over in favor of one that isn't. So:</P>
<DIV class=3Ditemizedlist>
<UL type=3Ddisc>
  <LI>
  <P>Send plain text mail, not HTML. (It's not hard to <A class=3Dulink=20
  href=3D"http://expita.com/nomime.html" target=3D_top>turn off =
HTML</A>.)</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>MIME attachments are usually OK, but only if they are real content =
(such as=20
  an attached source file or patch), and not merely boilerplate =
generated by=20
  your mail client (such as another copy of your message).</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Don't send e-mail in which entire paragraphs are single =
multiply-wrapped=20
  lines. (This makes it too difficult to reply to just part of the =
message.)=20
  Assume that your respondents will be reading mail on 80-character-wide =
text=20
  displays and set your line wrap accordingly, to something less than=20
  80.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>However, do <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>not</EM></SPAN> wrap data =
(such as log=20
  file dumps or session transcripts) at any fixed column width. Data =
should be=20
  included as-is, so respondents can have confidence that they are =
seeing what=20
  you saw.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Don't send MIME Quoted-Printable encoding to an English-language =
forum.=20
  This encoding can be necessary when you're posting in a language ASCII =
doesn't=20
  cover, but many e-mail agents don't support it. When they break, all =
those =3D20=20
  glyphs scattered through the text are ugly and distracting =E2=80=94 =
or may actively=20
  sabotage the semantics of your text.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Never, <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>ever</EM></SPAN> expect hackers =
to be able=20
  to read closed proprietary document formats like Microsoft Word or =
Excel. Most=20
  hackers react to these about as well as you would to having a pile of =
steaming=20
  pig manure dumped on your doorstep. Even when they can cope, they =
resent=20
  having to do so.</P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>If you're sending e-mail from a Windows machine, turn off =
Microsoft's=20
  stupid =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Smart Quotes</SPAN>=E2=80=9D =
feature. This is so you'll=20
  avoid sprinkling garbage characters through your mail. </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>In Web forums, do not abuse =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>smiley</SPAN>=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
  class=3Dquote>HTML</SPAN>=E2=80=9D features (when they are present). A =
smiley or two is=20
  usually OK, but colored fancy text tends to make people think you are =
lame.=20
  Seriously overusing smileys and color and fonts will make you come off =
like a=20
  giggly teenage girl, which is not generally a good idea unless you are =
more=20
  interested in sex than answers.</P></LI></UL></DIV>
<P>If you're using a graphical-user-interface mail client such as =
Netscape=20
Messenger, MS Outlook, or their ilk, beware that it may violate these =
rules when=20
used with its default settings. Most such clients have a menu-based =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>View Source</SPAN>=E2=80=9D command. Use this on something =
in your sent-mail=20
folder, verifying sending of plain text without unnecessary attached=20
crud.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dbeprecise></A>Be precise and informative about =
your=20
problem</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<DIV class=3Ditemizedlist>
<UL type=3Ddisc>
  <LI>
  <P>Describe the symptoms of your problem or bug carefully and clearly. =

  </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Describe the environment in which it occurs (machine, OS, =
application,=20
  whatever). Provide your vendor's distribution and release level (e.g.: =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
  class=3Dquote>Fedora Core 7</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>Slackware 9.1</SPAN>=E2=80=9D,=20
  etc.). </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Describe the research you did to try and understand the problem =
before you=20
  asked the question. </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Describe the diagnostic steps you took to try and pin down the =
problem=20
  yourself before you asked the question. </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>Describe any possibly relevant recent changes in your computer or =
software=20
  configuration. </P></LI>
  <LI>
  <P>If at all possible, provide a way to <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>reproduce the=20
  problem in a controlled environment</EM></SPAN>. </P></LI></UL></DIV>
<P>Do the best you can to anticipate the questions a hacker will ask, =
and answer=20
them in advance in your request for help.</P>
<P>Giving hackers the ability to reproduce the problem in a controlled=20
environment is especially important if you are reporting something you =
think is=20
a bug in code. When you do this, your odds of getting a useful answer =
and the=20
speed with which you are likely to get that answer both improve=20
tremendously.</P>
<P>Simon Tatham has written an excellent essay entitled <A class=3Dulink =

href=3D"http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/bugs.html" =
target=3D_top>How to=20
Report Bugs Effectively</A>. I strongly recommend that you read =
it.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dvolume></A>Volume is not =
precision</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>You need to be precise and informative. This end is not served by =
simply=20
dumping huge volumes of code or data into a help request. If you have a =
large,=20
complicated test case that is breaking a program, try to trim it and =
make it as=20
small as possible.</P>
<P>This is useful for at least three reasons. One: being seen to invest =
effort=20
in simplifying the question makes it more likely you'll get an answer, =
Two:=20
simplifying the question makes it more likely you'll get a <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>useful</EM></SPAN> answer. Three: In the process of =
refining=20
your bug report, you may develop a fix or workaround yourself.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Did382249></A>Don't rush to claim that you have =
found a=20
bug</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>When you are having problems with a piece of software, don't claim =
you have=20
found a bug unless you are very, <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>very</EM></SPAN> sure=20
of your ground. Hint: unless you can provide a source-code patch that =
fixes the=20
problem, or a regression test against a previous version that =
demonstrates=20
incorrect behavior, you are probably not sure enough. This applies to =
webpages=20
and documentation, too; if you have found a documentation =E2=80=9C<SPAN =

class=3Dquote>bug</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, you should supply replacement text =
and which pages it=20
should go on.</P>
<P>Remember, there are many other users that are not experiencing your =
problem.=20
Otherwise you would have learned about it while reading the =
documentation and=20
searching the Web (you did do that before complaining, <A class=3Dlink=20
title=3D"Before You Ask"=20
href=3D"http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/smart-questions.html#before">didn't=
=20
you</A>?). This means that very probably it is you who are doing =
something=20
wrong, not the software.</P>
<P>The people who wrote the software work very hard to make it work as =
well as=20
possible. If you claim you have found a bug, you'll be impugning their=20
competence, which may offend some of them even if you are correct. It's=20
especially undiplomatic to yell =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>bug</SPAN>=E2=80=9D in the Subject=20
line.</P>
<P>When asking your question, it is best to write as though you assume =
<SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>you</EM></SPAN> are doing something wrong, even if =
you are=20
privately pretty sure you have found an actual bug. If there really is a =
bug,=20
you will hear about it in the answer. Play it so the maintainers will =
want to=20
apologize to you if the bug is real, rather than so that you will owe =
them an=20
apology if you have messed up.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Did382403></A>Grovelling is not a substitute =
for doing your=20
homework</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Some people who get that they shouldn't behave rudely or arrogantly,=20
demanding an answer, retreat to the opposite extreme of grovelling. =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>I know I'm just a pathetic newbie loser, =
but...</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. This is=20
distracting and unhelpful. It's especially annoying when it's coupled =
with=20
vagueness about the actual problem.</P>
<P>Don't waste your time, or ours, on crude primate politics. Instead, =
present=20
the background facts and your question as clearly as you can. That is a =
better=20
way to position yourself than by grovelling.</P>
<P>Sometimes Web forums have separate places for newbie questions. If =
you feel=20
you do have a newbie question, just go there. But don't grovel there=20
either.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dsymptoms></A>Describe the problem's symptoms, =
not your=20
guesses</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>It's not useful to tell hackers what you think is causing your =
problem. (If=20
your diagnostic theories were such hot stuff, would you be consulting =
others for=20
help?) So, make sure you're telling them the raw symptoms of what goes =
wrong,=20
rather than your interpretations and theories. Let them do the =
interpretation=20
and diagnosis. If you feel it's important to state your guess, clearly =
label it=20
as such and describe why that answer isn't working for you.</P>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN>=20
  </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>I'm getting back-to-back SIG11 errors on kernel compiles, and =
suspect a=20
  hairline crack on one of the motherboard traces. What's the best way =
to check=20
  for those?</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN>=20
  </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>My home-built K6/233 on an FIC-PA2007 motherboard (VIA Apollo VP2 =
chipset)=20
  with 256MB Corsair PC133 SDRAM starts getting frequent SIG11 errors =
about 20=20
  minutes after power-on during the course of kernel compiles, but never =
in the=20
  first 20 minutes. Rebooting doesn't restart the clock, but powering =
down=20
  overnight does. Swapping out all RAM didn't help. The relevant part of =
a=20
  typical compile session log follows.</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<P>Since the preceding point seems to be a tough one for many people to =
grasp,=20
here's a phrase to remind you: "All diagnosticians are from Missouri." =
That US=20
state's official motto is "Show me" (earned in 1899, when Congressman =
Willard D.=20
Vandiver said "I come from a country that raises corn and cotton and =
cockleburs=20
and Democrats, and frothy eloquence neither convinces nor satisfies me. =
I'm from=20
Missouri. You've got to show me.") In diagnosticians' case, it's not a =
matter of=20
skepticism, but rather a literal, functional need to see whatever is as =
close as=20
possible to the same raw evidence that you see, rather than your =
surmises and=20
summaries. Show us.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dchronology></A>Describe your problem's =
symptoms in=20
chronological order</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>The clues most useful in figuring out something that went wrong often =
lie in=20
the events immediately prior. So, your account should describe precisely =
what=20
you did, and what the machine and software did, leading up to the =
blowup. In the=20
case of command-line processes, having a session log (e.g., using the =
script=20
utility) and quoting the relevant twenty or so lines is very useful.</P>
<P>If the program that blew up on you has diagnostic options (such as -v =
for=20
verbose), try to select options that will add useful debugging =
information to=20
the transcript. Remember that more is not necessarily better; try to =
choose a=20
debug level that will inform rather than drowning the reader in =
junk.</P>
<P>If your account ends up being long (more than about four paragraphs), =
it=20
might be useful to succinctly state the problem up top, then follow with =
the=20
chronological tale. That way, hackers will know what to watch for in =
reading=20
your account.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dgoal></A>Describe the goal, not the=20
step</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>If you are trying to find out how to do something (as opposed to =
reporting a=20
bug), begin by describing the goal. Only then describe the particular =
step=20
towards it that you are blocked on.</P>
<P>Often, people who need technical help have a high-level goal in mind =
and get=20
stuck on what they think is one particular path towards the goal. They =
come for=20
help with the step, but don't realize that the path is wrong. It can =
take=20
substantial effort to get past this.</P>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN>=20
  </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>How do I get the color-picker on the FooDraw program to take a =
hexadecimal=20
  RGB value?</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN>=20
  </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>I'm trying to replace the color table on an image with values of my =

  choosing. Right now the only way I can see to do this is by editing =
each table=20
  slot, but I can't get FooDraw's color picker to take a hexadecimal RGB =

  value.</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<P>The second version of the question is smart. It allows an answer that =

suggests a tool better suited to the task.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dnoprivate></A>Don't ask people to reply by =
private=20
e-mail</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Hackers believe solving problems should be a public, transparent =
process=20
during which a first try at an answer can and should be corrected if =
someone=20
more knowledgeable notices that it is incomplete or incorrect. Also, =
helpers get=20
some of their reward for being respondents from being seen to be =
competent and=20
knowledgeable by their peers.</P>
<P>When you ask for a private reply, you are disrupting both the process =
and the=20
reward. Don't do this. It's the <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>respondent's</EM></SPAN> choice whether to reply =
privately =E2=80=94=20
and if he does, it's usually because he thinks the question is too =
ill-formed or=20
obvious to be interesting to others.</P>
<P>There is one limited exception to this rule. If you think the =
question is=20
such that you are likely to get many answers that are all closely =
similar, then=20
the magic words are =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>e-mail me and I'll =
summarize the answers=20
for the group</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. It is courteous to try and save the =
mailing list or=20
newsgroup a flood of substantially identical postings =E2=80=94 but you =
have to keep the=20
promise to summarize.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dexplicit></A>Be explicit about your=20
question</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Open-ended questions tend to be perceived as open-ended time sinks. =
Those=20
people most likely to be able to give you a useful answer are also the =
busiest=20
people (if only because they take on the most work themselves). People =
like that=20
are allergic to open-ended time sinks, thus they tend to be allergic to=20
open-ended questions.</P>
<P>You are more likely to get a useful response if you are explicit =
about what=20
you want respondents to do (provide pointers, send code, check your =
patch,=20
whatever). This will focus their effort and implicitly put an upper =
bound on the=20
time and energy a respondent must allocate to helping you. This is =
good.</P>
<P>To understand the world the experts live in, think of expertise as an =

abundant resource and time to respond as a scarce one. The less of a =
time=20
commitment you implicitly ask for, the more likely you are to get an =
answer from=20
someone really good and really busy.</P>
<P>So it is useful to frame your question to minimize the time =
commitment=20
required for an expert to field it =E2=80=94 but this is often not the =
same thing as=20
simplifying the question. Thus, for example, =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>Would you give=20
me a pointer to a good explanation of X?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D is usually a =
smarter question=20
than =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Would you explain X, =
please?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. If you have some=20
malfunctioning code, it is usually smarter to ask for someone to explain =
what's=20
wrong with it than it is to ask someone to fix it.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dcode></A>When asking about =
code</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Don't ask others to debug your broken code without giving a hint what =
sort of=20
problem they should be searching for. Posting a few hundred lines of =
code,=20
saying "it doesn't work", will get you ignored. Posting a dozen lines of =
code,=20
saying "after line 7 I was expecting to see &lt;x&gt;, but &lt;y&gt; =
occurred=20
instead" is much more likely to get you a response.</P>
<P>The most effective way to be precise about a code problem is to =
provide a=20
minimal bug-demonstrating test case. What's a minimal test case? It's an =

illustration of the problem; just enough code to exhibit the undesirable =

behavior and no more. How do you make a minimal test case? If you know =
what line=20
or section of code is producing the problematic behavior, make a copy of =
it and=20
add just enough supporting code to produce a complete example (i.e. =
enough that=20
the source is acceptable to the compiler/interpreter/whatever =
application=20
processes it). If you can't narrow it down to a particular section, make =
a copy=20
of the source and start removing chunks that don't affect the =
problematic=20
behavior. The smaller your minimal test case is, the better (see <A =
class=3Dxref=20
title=3D"Volume is not precision"=20
href=3D"http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/smart-questions.html#volume">the =
section=20
called =E2=80=9CVolume is not precision=E2=80=9D</A>).</P>
<P>Generating a really small minimal test case will not always be =
possible, but=20
trying to is good discipline. It may help you learn what you need to =
solve the=20
problem on your own =E2=80=94 and even when it doesn't, hackers like to =
see that you=20
have tried. It will make them more cooperative.</P>
<P>If you simply want a code review, say as much up front, and be sure =
to=20
mention what areas you think might particularly need review and =
why.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dhomework></A>Don't post homework=20
questions</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Hackers are good at spotting homework questions; most of us have done =
them=20
ourselves. Those questions are for <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>you</EM></SPAN> to=20
work out, so that you will learn from the experience. It is OK to ask =
for hints,=20
but not for entire solutions.</P>
<P>If you suspect you have been passed a homework question, but can't =
solve it=20
anyway, try asking in a user group forum or (as a last resort) in a =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>user</SPAN>=E2=80=9D list/forum of a project. While the =
hackers <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>will</EM></SPAN> spot it, some of the advanced =
users may at=20
least give you a hint.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dprune></A>Prune pointless =
queries</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Resist the temptation to close your request for help with =
semantically-null=20
questions like =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Can anyone help =
me?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Is there an answer?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D First: if you've =
written your problem=20
description halfway competently, such tacked-on questions are at best=20
superfluous. Second: because they are superfluous, hackers find them =
annoying =E2=80=94=20
and are likely to return logically impeccable but dismissive answers =
like =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Yes, you can be helped</SPAN>=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>No, there is=20
no help for you.</SPAN>=E2=80=9D</P>
<P>In general, asking yes-or-no questions is a good thing to avoid =
unless you=20
want a <A class=3Dulink=20
href=3D"http://homepages.tesco.net/~J.deBoynePollard/FGA/questions-with-y=
es-or-no-answers.html"=20
target=3D_top>yes-or-no answer</A>.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Durgent></A>Don't flag your question as =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Urgent</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, even if it is for =
you</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>That's your problem, not ours. Claiming urgency is very likely to be=20
counter-productive: most hackers will simply delete such messages as =
rude and=20
selfish attempts to elicit immediate and special attention.</P>
<P>There is one semi-exception. It can be worth mentioning if you're =
using the=20
program in some high-profile place, one that the hackers will get =
excited about;=20
in such a case, if you're under time pressure, and you say so politely, =
people=20
may get interested enough to answer faster.</P>
<P>This is a very risky thing to do, however, because the hackers' =
metric for=20
what is exciting probably differs from yours. Posting from the =
International=20
Space Station would qualify, for example, but posting on behalf of a =
feel-good=20
charitable or political cause would almost certainly not. In fact, =
posting=20
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Urgent: Help me save the fuzzy baby =
seals!</SPAN>=E2=80=9D will=20
reliably get you shunned or flamed even by hackers who think fuzzy baby =
seals=20
are important.</P>
<P>If you find this mysterious, re-read the rest of this how-to =
repeatedly until=20
you understand it before posting anything at all.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dcourtesy></A>Courtesy never hurts, and =
sometimes=20
helps</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Be courteous. Use =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Please</SPAN>=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Thanks for your attention</SPAN>=E2=80=9D or =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Thanks for=20
your consideration</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. Make it clear you appreciate the =
time people spend=20
helping you for free.</P>
<P>To be honest, this isn't as important as (and cannot substitute for) =
being=20
grammatical, clear, precise and descriptive, avoiding proprietary =
formats etc.;=20
hackers in general would rather get somewhat brusque but technically =
sharp bug=20
reports than polite vagueness. (If this puzzles you, remember that we =
value a=20
question by what it teaches us.)</P>
<P>However, if you've got your technical ducks in a row, politeness does =

increase your chances of getting a useful answer.</P>
<P>(We must note that the only serious objection we've received from =
veteran=20
hackers to this HOWTO is with respect to our previous recommendation to =
use=20
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Thanks in advance</SPAN>=E2=80=9D. Some =
hackers feel this connotes an=20
intention not to thank anybody afterwards. Our recommendation is to =
either say=20
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Thanks in advance</SPAN>=E2=80=9D first =
<SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>and</EM></SPAN> thank respondents afterwards, or =
express=20
courtesy in a different way, such as by saying =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>Thanks for=20
your attention</SPAN>=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Thanks =
for your=20
consideration</SPAN>=E2=80=9D.)</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dfollowup></A>Follow up with a brief note on =
the=20
solution</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Send a note after the problem has been solved to all who helped you; =
let them=20
know how it came out and thank them again for their help. If the problem =

attracted general interest in a mailing list or newsgroup, it's =
appropriate to=20
post the followup there.</P>
<P>Optimally, the reply should be to the thread started by the original =
question=20
posting, and should have =E2=80=98FIXED=E2=80=99, =
=E2=80=98RESOLVED=E2=80=99 or an equally obvious tag in the=20
subject line. On mailing lists with fast turnaround, a potential =
respondent who=20
sees a thread about =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Problem =
X</SPAN>=E2=80=9D ending with =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Problem X - FIXED</SPAN>=E2=80=9D knows not to waste =
his/her time even=20
reading the thread (unless (s)he) personally finds Problem X =
interesting) and=20
can therefore use that time solving a different problem.</P>
<P>Your followup doesn't have to be long and involved; a simple =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Howdy =E2=80=94 it was a failed network cable! Thanks, =
everyone. -=20
Bill</SPAN>=E2=80=9D would be better than nothing. In fact, a short and =
sweet summary is=20
better than a long dissertation unless the solution has real technical =
depth.=20
Say what action solved the problem, but you need not replay the whole=20
troubleshooting sequence.</P>
<P>For problems with some depth, it is appropriate to post a summary of =
the=20
troubleshooting history. Describe your final problem statement. Describe =
what=20
worked as a solution, and indicate avoidable blind alleys <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>after that</EM></SPAN>. The blind alleys should =
come after=20
the correct solution and other summary material, rather than turning the =

follow-up into a detective story. Name the names of people who helped =
you;=20
you'll make friends that way.</P>
<P>Besides being courteous and informative, this sort of followup will =
help=20
others searching the archive of the mailing-list/newsgroup/forum to know =
exactly=20
which solution helped you and thus may also help them.</P>
<P>Last, and not least, this sort of followup helps everybody who =
assisted feel=20
a satisfying sense of closure about the problem. If you are not a techie =
or=20
hacker yourself, trust us that this feeling is very important to the =
gurus and=20
experts you tapped for help. Problem narratives that trail off into =
unresolved=20
nothingness are frustrating things; hackers itch to see them resolved. =
The=20
goodwill that scratching that itch earns you will be very, very helpful =
to you=20
next time you need to pose a question. </P>
<P>Consider how you might be able to prevent others from having the same =
problem=20
in the future. Ask yourself if a documentation or FAQ patch would help, =
and if=20
the answer is yes send that patch to the maintainer.</P>
<P>Among hackers, this sort of good followup behavior is actually more =
important=20
than conventional politeness. It's how you get a reputation for playing =
well=20
with others, which can be a very valuable asset.</P></DIV></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Danswers></A>How To =
Interpret=20
Answers</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Drtfm></A>RTFM and STFW: How To Tell You've =
Seriously=20
Screwed Up</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>There is an ancient and hallowed tradition: if you get a reply that =
reads=20
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>RTFM</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, the person who sent =
it thinks you should have=20
Read The Fucking Manual. He or she is almost certainly right. Go read =
it.</P>
<P>RTFM has a younger relative. If you get a reply that reads =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>STFW</SPAN>=E2=80=9D, the person who sent it thinks you =
should have Searched=20
The Fucking Web. He or she is almost certainly right. Go search it. (The =
milder=20
version of this is when you are told =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Google =
is your=20
friend!</SPAN>=E2=80=9D)</P>
<P>In Web forums, you may also be told to search the forum archives. In =
fact,=20
someone may even be so kind as to provide a pointer to the previous =
thread where=20
this problem was solved. But do not rely on this consideration; do your=20
archive-searching before asking.</P>
<P>Often, the person telling you to do a search has the manual or the =
web page=20
with the information you need open, and is looking at it as he or she =
types.=20
These replies mean that he thinks (a) the information you need is easy =
to find,=20
and (b) you will learn more if you seek out the information than if you =
have it=20
spoon-fed to you.</P>
<P>You shouldn't be offended by this; by hacker standards, your =
respondent is=20
showing you a rough kind of respect simply by not ignoring you. You =
should=20
instead be thankful for this grandmotherly kindness.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dlesser></A>If you don't=20
understand...</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>If you don't understand the answer, do not immediately bounce back a =
demand=20
for clarification. Use the same tools that you used to try and answer =
your=20
original question (manuals, FAQs, the Web, skilled friends) to =
understand the=20
answer. Then, if you still need to ask for clarification, exhibit what =
you have=20
learned.</P>
<P>For example, suppose I tell you: =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>It =
sounds like you've got=20
a stuck zentry; you'll need to clear it.</SPAN>=E2=80=9D Then: here's a =
<SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>bad</EM></SPAN> followup question: =E2=80=9C<SPAN =
class=3Dquote>What's=20
a zentry?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D Here's a <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>good</EM></SPAN> followup=20
question: =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>OK, I read the man page and =
zentries are only=20
mentioned under the -z and -p switches. Neither of them says anything =
about=20
clearing zentries. Is it one of these or am I missing something=20
here?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect2 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H3 class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dkeepcool></A>Dealing with =
rudeness</H3></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Much of what looks like rudeness in hacker circles is not intended to =
give=20
offense. Rather, it's the product of the direct, =
cut-through-the-bullshit=20
communications style that is natural to people who are more concerned =
about=20
solving problems than making others feel warm and fuzzy.</P>
<P>When you perceive rudeness, try to react calmly. If someone is really =
acting=20
out, it is very likely a senior person on the list or newsgroup or forum =
will=20
call him or her on it. If that <SPAN =
class=3Demphasis><EM>doesn't</EM></SPAN>=20
happen and you lose your temper, it is likely that the person you lose =
it at was=20
behaving within the hacker community's norms and <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>you</EM></SPAN> will be considered at fault. This =
will hurt=20
your chances of getting the information or help you want.</P>
<P>On the other hand, you will occasionally run across rudeness and =
posturing=20
that is quite gratuitous. The flip-side of the above is that it is =
acceptable=20
form to slam real offenders quite hard, dissecting their misbehavior =
with a=20
sharp verbal scalpel. Be very, very sure of your ground before you try =
this,=20
however. The line between correcting an incivility and starting a =
pointless=20
flamewar is thin enough that hackers themselves not infrequently blunder =
across=20
it; if you are a newbie or an outsider, your chances of avoiding such a =
blunder=20
are low. If you're after information rather than entertainment, it's =
better to=20
keep your fingers off the keyboard than to risk this.</P>
<P>(Some people assert that many hackers have a mild form of autism or=20
Asperger's Syndrome, and are actually missing some of the brain =
circuitry that=20
lubricates =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>normal</SPAN>=E2=80=9D human =
social interaction. This may=20
or may not be true. If you are not a hacker yourself, it may help you =
cope with=20
our eccentricities if you think of us as being brain-damaged. Go right =
ahead. We=20
won't care; we <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>like</EM></SPAN> being =
whatever it is we=20
are, and generally have a healthy skepticism about clinical labels.)</P>
<P>In the next section, we'll talk about a different issue; the kind of =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>rudeness</SPAN>=E2=80=9D you'll see when <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>you</EM></SPAN> misbehave.</P></DIV></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Dnot_losing></A>On Not =
Reacting Like A=20
Loser</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>Odds are you'll screw up a few times on hacker community forums =
=E2=80=94 in ways=20
detailed in this article, or similar. And you'll be told exactly how you =
screwed=20
up, possibly with colourful asides. In public.</P>
<P>When this happens, the worst thing you can do is whine about the =
experience,=20
claim to have been verbally assaulted, demand apologies, scream, hold =
your=20
breath, threaten lawsuits, complain to people's employers, leave the =
toilet seat=20
up, etc. Instead, here's what you do:</P>
<P>Get over it. It's normal. In fact, it's healthy and appropriate.</P>
<P>Community standards do not maintain themselves: They're maintained by =
people=20
actively applying them, visibly, <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>in =
public</EM></SPAN>.=20
Don't whine that all criticism should have been conveyed via private =
e-mail:=20
That's not how it works. Nor is it useful to insist you've been =
personally=20
insulted when someone comments that one of your claims was wrong, or =
that his=20
views differ. Those are loser attitudes.</P>
<P>There have been hacker forums where, out of some misguided sense of=20
hyper-courtesy, participants are banned from posting any fault-finding =
with=20
another's posts, and told =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Don't say =
anything if you're=20
unwilling to help the user.</SPAN>=E2=80=9D The resulting departure of =
clueful=20
participants to elsewhere causes them to descend into meaningless babble =
and=20
become useless as technical forums.</P>
<P>Exaggeratedly =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>friendly</SPAN>=E2=80=9D =
(in that fashion) or=20
useful: Pick one.</P>
<P>Remember: When that hacker tells you that you've screwed up, and (no =
matter=20
how gruffly) tells you not to do it again, he's acting out of concern =
for (1)=20
you and (2) his community. It would be much easier for him to ignore you =
and=20
filter you out of his life. If you can't manage to be grateful, at least =
have a=20
little dignity, don't whine, and don't expect to be treated like a =
fragile doll=20
just because you're a newcomer with a theatrically hypersensitive soul =
and=20
delusions of entitlement.</P>
<P>Sometimes people will attack you personally, flame without an =
apparent=20
reason, etc., even if you don't screw up (or have only screwed up in =
their=20
imagination). In this case, complaining is the way to <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>really</EM></SPAN> screw up.</P>
<P>These flamers are either lamers who don't have a clue but believe =
themselves=20
to be experts, or would-be psychologists testing whether you'll screw =
up. The=20
other readers either ignore them, or find ways to deal with them on =
their own.=20
The flamers' behavior creates problems for themselves, which don't have =
to=20
concern you.</P>
<P>Don't let yourself be drawn into a flamewar, either. Most flames are =
best=20
ignored =E2=80=94 after you've checked whether they are really flames, =
not pointers to=20
the ways in which you have screwed up, and not cleverly ciphered answers =
to your=20
real question (this happens as well).</P></DIV>
