<P>Finally, I'm going to illustrate how to ask questions in a smart way =
by=20
example; pairs of questions about the same problem, one asked in a =
stupid way=20
and one in a smart way.</P>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN> Where=20
  can I find out stuff about the Foonly Flurbamatic? </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This question just begs for <A class=3Dlink=20
  title=3D"RTFM and STFW: How To Tell You've Seriously Screwed Up"=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.catb.org/~esr/faqs/smart-questions.html#rtfm">"STFW"</=
A> as a=20
  reply.</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN> I used=20
  Google to try to find =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Foonly Flurbamatic =
2600</SPAN>=E2=80=9D on=20
  the Web, but I got no useful hits. Can I get a pointer to programming=20
  information on this device? </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This one has already STFWed, and sounds like he might have a real=20
  problem.</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN> I=20
  can't get the code from project foo to compile. Why is it broken? =
</SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The querent assumes that somebody else screwed up. Arrogant =
git...</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN> The=20
  code from project foo doesn't compile under Nulix version 6.2. I've =
read the=20
  FAQ, but it doesn't have anything in it about Nulix-related problems. =
Here's a=20
  transcript of my compilation attempt; is it something I did? =
</SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>The querent has specified the environment, read the FAQ, is showing =
the=20
  error, and is not assuming his problems are someone else's fault. This =
one=20
  might be worth some attention.</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dvariablelist>
<DL>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Stupid:</STRONG></SPAN> I'm=20
  having problems with my motherboard. Can anybody help? </SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>J. Random Hacker's response to this is likely to be =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
  class=3Dquote>Right. Do you need burping and diapering, =
too?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D followed by=20
  a punch of the delete key.</P></DD>
  <DT><SPAN class=3Dterm><SPAN =
class=3Dstrong><STRONG>Smart:</STRONG></SPAN> I tried=20
  X, Y, and Z on the S2464 motherboard. When that didn't work, I tried =
A, B, and=20
  C. Note the curious symptom when I tried C. Obviously the florbish is=20
  grommicking, but the results aren't what one might expect. What are =
the usual=20
  causes of grommicking on Athlon MP motherboards? Anybody got ideas for =
more=20
  tests I can run to pin down the problem?</SPAN></DT>
  <DD>
  <P>This person, on the other hand, seems worthy of an answer. He/she =
has=20
  exhibited problem-solving intelligence rather than passively waiting =
for an=20
  answer to drop from on high.</P></DD></DL></DIV>
<P>In the last question, notice the subtle but important difference =
between=20
demanding =E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>Give me an answer</SPAN>=E2=80=9D =
and =E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>Please help me figure out what additional diagnostics I =
can run to=20
achieve enlightenment.</SPAN>=E2=80=9D</P>
<P>In fact, the form of that last question is closely based on a real =
incident=20
that happened in August 2001 on the linux-kernel mailing list (lkml). I =
(Eric)=20
was the one asking the question that time. I was seeing mysterious =
lockups on a=20
Tyan S2462 motherboard. The list members supplied the critical =
information I=20
needed to solve them.</P>
<P>By asking the question in the way I did, I gave people something to =
chew on;=20
I made it easy and attractive for them to get involved. I demonstrated =
respect=20
for my peers' ability and invited them to consult with me as a peer. I =
also=20
demonstrated respect for the value of their time by telling them the =
blind=20
alleys I had already run down.</P>
<P>Afterwards, when I thanked everyone and remarked how well the process =
had=20
worked, an lkml member observed that he thought it had worked not =
because I'm a=20
=E2=80=9C<SPAN class=3Dquote>name</SPAN>=E2=80=9D on that list, but =
because I asked the question=20
in the proper form.</P>
<P>Hackers are in some ways a very ruthless meritocracy; I'm certain he =
was=20
right, and that if I <SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>had</EM></SPAN> behaved =
like a=20
sponge I would have been flamed or ignored no matter who I was. His =
suggestion=20
that I write up the whole incident as instruction to others led directly =
to the=20
composition of this guide.</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Did383575></A>If You =
Can't Get An=20
Answer</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P>If you can't get an answer, please don't take it personally that we =
don't=20
feel we can help you. Sometimes the members of the asked group may =
simply not=20
know the answer. No response is not the same as being ignored, though =
admittedly=20
it's hard to spot the difference from outside.</P>
<P>In general, simply re-posting your question is a bad idea. This will =
be seen=20
as pointlessly annoying. Have patience: the person with your answer may =
be in a=20
different time-zone and asleep. Or it may be that your question wasn't=20
well-formed to begin with.</P>
<P>There are other sources of help you can go to, often sources better =
adapted=20
to a novice's needs.</P>
<P>There are many online and local user groups who are enthusiasts about =
the=20
software, even though they may never have written any software =
themselves. These=20
groups often form so that people can help each other and help new =
users.</P>
<P>There are also plenty of commercial companies you can contract with =
for help,=20
both large and small (Red Hat and SpikeSource are two of the best known; =
there=20
are many others). Don't be dismayed at the idea of having to pay for a =
bit of=20
help! After all, if your car engine blows a head gasket, chances are you =
would=20
take it to a repair shop and pay to get it fixed. Even if the software =
didn't=20
cost you anything, you can't expect that support to always come for =
free.</P>
<P>For popular software like Linux, there are at least 10,000 users per=20
developer. It's just not possible for one person to handle the support =
calls=20
from over 10,000 users. Remember that even if you have to pay for =
support, you=20
are still paying much less than if you had to buy the software as well =
(and=20
support for closed-source software is usually more expensive and less =
competent=20
than support for open-source software).</P></DIV>
<DIV lang=3Den class=3Dsect1 xml:lang=3D"en">
<DIV class=3Dtitlepage>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<H2 style=3D"CLEAR: both" class=3Dtitle><A id=3Did383614></A>How To =
Answer Questions=20
in a Helpful Way</H2></DIV></DIV></DIV>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>Be gentle.</EM></SPAN> Problem-related =
stress can=20
make people seem rude or stupid even when they're not.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>Reply to a first offender =
off-line.</EM></SPAN>=20
There is no need of public humiliation for someone who may have made an =
honest=20
mistake. A real newbie may not know how to search archives or where the =
FAQ is=20
stored or posted.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>If you don't know for sure, say =
so!</EM></SPAN> A=20
wrong but authoritative-sounding answer is worse than none at all. Don't =
point=20
anyone down a wrong path simply because it's fun to sound like an =
expert. Be=20
humble and honest; set a good example for both the querent and your =
peers.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>If you can't help, don't =
hinder.</EM></SPAN> Don't=20
make jokes about procedures that could trash the user's setup =E2=80=94 =
the poor sap=20
might interpret these as instructions.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>Ask probing questions to elicit more=20
details.</EM></SPAN> If you're good at this, the querent will learn =
something =E2=80=94=20
and so might you. Try to turn the bad question into a good one; remember =
we were=20
all newbies once.</P>
<P>While muttering RTFM is sometimes justified when replying to someone =
who is=20
just a lazy slob, a pointer to documentation (even if it's just a =
suggestion to=20
google for a key phrase) is better.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>If you're going to answer the question at =
all, give=20
good value.</EM></SPAN> Don't suggest kludgy workarounds when somebody =
is using=20
the wrong tool or approach. Suggest good tools. Reframe the =
question.</P>
<P><SPAN class=3Demphasis><EM>Help your community learn from the=20
question.</EM></SPAN> When you field a good question, ask yourself =
=E2=80=9C<SPAN=20
class=3Dquote>How would the relevant documentation or FAQ have to change =
so that=20
nobody has to answer this again?</SPAN>=E2=80=9D Then send a patch to =
the document=20
maintainer.</P>
<P>If you did research to answer the question, <SPAN=20
class=3Demphasis><EM>demonstrate your skills rather than writing as =
though you=20
pulled the answer out of your butt.</EM></SPAN> Answering one good =
question is=20
like feeding a hungry person one meal, but teaching them research skills =
by=20
example is showing them how to grow food for a lifetime.</P></DIV>
